TITLE: Expression Path Syntax Definition
DESCRIPTION: Defines the grammar for paths in expressions, including the use of generic arguments and special path identifiers. It explains the `turbofish` syntax used in Rust to distinguish between generics and operators.
SOURCE: https://github.com/rust-lang/reference.git/blob/master/src/paths.md#2025-04-21_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: grammar
CODE:
```
PathInExpression ->
    `::`? PathExprSegment (`::` PathExprSegment)*

PathExprSegment ->
    PathIdentSegment (`::` GenericArgs)?

PathIdentSegment ->
    IDENTIFIER | `super` | `self` | `Self` | `crate` | `$crate`

GenericArgs ->
      `<` `>`
    | `<` ( GenericArg `,` )* GenericArg `,`? `>`

GenericArg ->
    Lifetime | Type | GenericArgsConst | GenericArgsBinding | GenericArgsBounds

GenericArgsConst ->
      BlockExpression
    | LiteralExpression
    | `-` LiteralExpression
    | SimplePathSegment

GenericArgsBinding ->
    IDENTIFIER GenericArgs? `=` Type

GenericArgsBounds ->
    IDENTIFIER GenericArgs? `:` TypeParamBounds
```

