TITLE: Variance Computation in Tuples and Function Pointers
DESCRIPTION: This snippet showcases how variance is evaluated separately in tuples and function pointers in Rust. It implies no specific dependencies but requires a comprehension of variance mechanics. The inputs involve tuple and function pointer manipulations, outputting results based on how variance allows for shrinking or extending lifetimes in separate contexts.
SOURCE: https://github.com/rust-lang/reference.git/blob/master/src/subtyping.md#2025-04-21_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: rust
CODE:
```
# use std::cell::UnsafeCell;
fn generic_tuple<'short, 'long: 'short>(
    // 'long is used inside of a tuple in both a co- and invariant position.
    x: (&'long u32, UnsafeCell<&'long u32>),
) {
    // As the variance at these positions is computed separately,
    // we can freely shrink 'long in the covariant position.
    let _: (&'short u32, UnsafeCell<&'long u32>) = x;
}

fn takes_fn_ptr<'short, 'middle: 'short>(
    // 'middle is used in both a co- and contravariant position.
    f: fn(&'middle ()) -> &'middle (),
) {
    // As the variance at these positions is computed separately,
    // we can freely shrink 'middle in the covariant position
    // and extend it in the contravariant position.
    let _: fn(&'static ()) -> &'short () = f;
}
```

